The monthly sales of the company is amount of  $P\cdot Q$, and the variable monthly costs are $v\cdot Q$. So, if the company charges for the goods immediately, the monthly cash flow  is
$$\begin{align*}
\text{Cash flow with old policy}&=P\cdot Q-v\cdot Q\\
&=(P-v)\cdot Q
\end{align*}$$
If the company approves the credit for a certain number of days, then the quantity sold under the new policys will be $Q^{\prime}$, then the monthly sale is $P\cdot Q^{\prime}$, and the costs will be $v\cdot Q^{\prime}$.  Then, the monthly cash flow  is
$$\begin{align*}
\text{Cash flow with new policy}&=P\cdot Q^{\prime}-v\cdot Q^{\prime}\\
&=(P-v)\cdot Q^{\prime}
\end{align*}$$

And, the present value of the future incremental cash flows is 
$$\begin{align*}
PV&=\frac{\text{Cash flow with new policy}-\text{Cash flow with new policy}}{\text{Monthly required return}}\\
&=\frac{(P-v)(Q^{\prime}-Q)}{R}
\end{align*}$$
